---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import CtaBand from '../components/CtaBand.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About Spry — Building the World's Best Scam-Resilience Software"
  description="Why we're pointing the proven simulated-training playbook at the people scammers target most, with consent, dignity, and proof."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="kicker">About</p>
      <h1>Why we're building the world's best scam-resilience software.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        In 2025, Americans over 60 reported more losses to scams than ever before:
      </p>
      <ul class="stat-bullets">
        <li><strong>$7.7 billion</strong> reported lost, up <strong>59%</strong> in a single year</li>
        <li><strong>More than 200,000</strong> complaints filed with the FBI</li>
        <li><strong>$38,000</strong> lost by the average victim, enough to erase years of savings</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Behind every one of those numbers is a family, and often a retirement, changed by a
        single phone call or text.
      </p>
      <p>
        What struck us wasn't just the scale. It was the mismatch.
        <strong>If you've ever received a fake "phishing test" email at work, you've already had
        the world's best scam training.</strong> For more than a decade, virtually every major
        company, bank, and government agency has drilled its people against these exact tactics
        with simulated attacks and in-the-moment coaching. It's a proven, multibillion-dollar
        playbook with years of evidence behind it. Meanwhile, the standard offering for the
        people scammers actually target most is a pamphlet and a one-time seminar whose effect,
        research shows, fades within a month.
      </p>
      <p>
        Spry exists to close that gap: to take the most effective training method we know of
        and finally point it at the people who need it, with the consent, gentleness, and dignity
        that training someone you love demands.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--paper">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <h2>The founder</h2>
      <p>
        Spry is built by <strong>Bryce Wachtell</strong>. Bryce spent his career in strategy and
        operations — at Bain &amp; Company, on Google's central strategy team, and at an
        early-stage startup — and is affiliated with Stanford's Graduate School of Business.
        He's building Spry the way he believes protective products should be built:
        research-first, consent-first, and in close conversation with the fraud-prevention
        experts, families, and senior-care leaders it serves.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="prose">
        <h2>Our principles</h2>
        <p class="lede">Five commitments we hold ourselves to, in every drill, briefing, and report.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid--2" style="margin-top: 32px;">
        <div class="card principle">
          <h3>Research-built</h3>
          <p>
            Every drill and briefing traces back to published research and to the scams currently
            being reported to the FBI and FTC. When the evidence changes, the product changes.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card principle">
          <h3>Proof over promises</h3>
          <p>
            No training can guarantee protection, so we never claim it. Instead we show families
            measurable progress every month, and we make refunds easy when we haven't earned our
            keep.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card principle">
          <h3>Dignity first</h3>
          <p>
            We coach; we never shame, trick for tricks' sake, or talk down. The person practicing
            is the hero of this story, not the risk to be managed.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card principle">
          <h3>Consent always</h3>
          <p>
            Nobody receives a drill who hasn't personally said yes. Every channel is opt-in,
            opting out takes one reply, and nothing ever happens behind anyone's back.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card principle">
          <h3>Independence, not surveillance</h3>
          <p>
            We don't watch bank accounts or monitor anyone's life. Spry builds the skill that
            lets people keep confidently handling their own affairs — that's the whole point.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="prose" style="margin-top: 36px;">
        We're in early access and building with our founding families and partners. Want to shape
        it? <a href="/early-access">Get early access</a> or write us at
        <a href="mailto:hello@sprysafe.com">hello@sprysafe.com</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CtaBand />
</Base>

<style>
  .stat-bullets {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 1.2em;
    display: grid;
    gap: 10px;
  }
  .stat-bullets li {
    background: var(--white);
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--pine);
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 12px 18px;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
  }
  .stat-bullets strong { color: var(--pine-deep); }
  .principle h3 { font-size: 1.2rem; }
  .principle p { margin-bottom: 0; color: var(--ink-soft); font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1.55; }
</style>
